Business Day

Ronald D. Croatti, Uniform Company Chief and Undercover Boss, Dies at 74

By MATTHEW GOLDSTEINMAY 26, 2017



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






Ronald D. Croatti in an undated photo.

Credit
            W. Marc Bernsau/Boston Business Journal        



Ronald D. Croatti, the chief executive of UniFirst, who spent his entire professional life supplying uniforms and apparel to some of the biggest manufacturing companies, died on Tuesday in Boston. He was 74.The cause was complications of pneumonia, a company representative said.At UniFirst, Mr. Croatti led what began in 1936 as a family-owned business run by his father, Aldo, from a converted horse barn in Boston, where one washing machine cleaned uniforms for factory workers. He turned it into the second-largest supplier and cleaner of uniforms and garments in the United States, with about $1.5 billion in annual revenue.When he took over as chief executive in 1991, succeeding his father, UniFirst, based in Wilmington, Mass., had about $100 million in revenue.Today, UniFirst supplies uniforms to nearly two million people working for 300,000 businesses in the United States, Canada and Europe, many in the food service, health care and energy industries. Archer Daniels Midland, Berkshire Hathaway, Coca-Cola, Costco and Goodyear are among its customers. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





It also specializes in decontaminating garments worn by workers at nuclear facilities.Mr. Croatti gave the company a promotional boost in 2011 when he put on a green UniFirst uniform, a mustache and a shoulder-length gray wig for an episode of the CBS reality series “Undercover Boss.” Pretending to be a new employee named Mike Daniels, he visited several of UniFirst’s 240 facilities, where workers taught him how to load dirty uniforms into giant washing machines and package clothes for delivery.

Undercover Boss - Preview: 'UniFirst' Video by CBS

The original broadcast was viewed by more than 13 million people, and the company has credited Mr. Croatti’s appearance with attracting new business.“Ron took a huge risk by doing this, as we had no editing rights,” said Adam Soreff, UniFirst’s director of marketing. “It ended up being great advertising and huge exposure.”In the episode, Mr. Croatti revealed some of his personal life, including his grandfather’s death in an accident involving an industrial clothes washer. The program also showed him relaxing at his home in Londonderry, N.H., playing with his model train collection.UniFirst, which went public in 1983 under the name Interstate Uniform Service Company, has remained in the hands of the Croatti family, which controls a majority of the voting shares. Mr. Croatti’s sister, Cynthia, is a board member and executive vice president. Two of his sons, Michael and Matthew, work for the company, which changed its name to UniFirst in 1984.
